 @l.sch.7545  Except it isn't... Not really.... Intel Core Ultra / Arrow lake compute tiles and I believe Lunar Lake are TSMC N3 & N3B. They are stable. TSMC begins mass production of their 2 nm process later this year, and Samsung has stated they're also ready for 2 nm production. TSMC claims they will have their bridge 1.6nm chips starting risk production by 2026 and are still confident that they will hit the 1 nm mark by 2030. 

People get too hung up on process node for advancements. Sure, reduction in node size historically means more power efficient and more compute per square cm, but it also comes with challenges like heat density and frequency limitations. Smaller process nodes will be great for mobile devices, phones, smart watches, even laptops and tablets, but they won't likely be much good for gaming or other applications that are dependent on being able to run less than 6 or so threads really fast. Once we're down at 2nm and 1nm, you'll see processing at much lower sustained frequencies, with much shorter boost capabilities. A device with applications that can make effective use of 30+ ultra low-power/low-frequency cores will be a good fit for these process nodes, while use cases like top-tier gaming might stop at 3nm and search for other improvements, scale out more cores, etc.  That's what we see with RTX 5090, they stayed on the same node as 4000 series, made minor generational improvements to their RT & tensor cores, left CUDA alone but just added gobs more of them. The increase in power consumption for the 33% additional cores in the 5090 gets offset by the roughly 25% increase in die size over the 4090 which actually gave the 5090 die a 5% lower transistor density than the 4090 (interestingly they increased cores by 33% but only had to increase total transistor count by 22%), the huge increase in compute cores allowed them to also reduce the frequency by 10% which lowered the thermal output per square mm even further and made the die much easier to cool. Nvidia could certainly continue down that path... 

Multi-chip-module must be the future for GPU's and CPU's, that's what would allow them to continuing to scale out for a long time without requiring extremely costly monolithic dies with massively high yields. AMD with Ryzen showed that it was possible to scale from 4 cores, to 8 cores, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 96, 128 and now 192 cores per "chip". If they put the R&D into figuring out how to solve MCM with GPU's, it's technically possible for Nvidia or AMD to give us a GPU that meets RTX 5090 raw performance on a MCM with four interconnected chips similar to RTX 5070 in die size and performance, maybe 250 sq mm per chip and around 6144 CUDA cores/192 SM's per chiplet, or, 24,576 cores/768 SM's on the entire GPU MCM. The costs to produce would be FAR cheaper than a single 5090 Blackwell die, Nvidia might be able to bring switchless NV-HBI down to the MCM layer as a low-cost MCM NOC in a few years, something that could create a full mesh between the four MCM's, each GPU chiplet having it's own smaller local HBM pool and something like NV-HBI for at least 2x10 TB/s to each of the three other GPU chiplets. That Nvidia AI datacenter tech is crazy expensive now, but they could commoditize it to run on an MCM architecture similar to Intel FOVEROS in a few years. Start with two GPU chiplet MCM, then scale as NV-HBI gets cheaper and faster.

